<br>
_______________________________________________________<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Marina crossed the platform in the city of Kelethin with her head held high despite<br>
                      the whispers that<br>
                      followed her. The days of hanging her head around the woodelven folk who inhabited<br>
                      the city were long<br>
                      gone. This was her home, her place of solace. And so much the worse for the those<br>
                      who thought she<br>
                      didn't belong here any longer. <br>
<br>
                      She had been born here in the city to parents who were very involved in the defense<br>
                      of the city when the<br>
                      orcs had moved into the forests. Her mother, a powerful druid, had been assured at<br>
                      Marina's birth that she<br>
                      now had the child who would follow in her footsteps and protect all the Mother had<br>
                      created. She began<br>
                      teaching Marina the ways of the druids almost before she was out of the cradle.<br>
                      Unfortunately Marina had<br>
                      little, if any aptitude in the ways of spells and such. The day she set her mothers<br>
                      best tablecloth on fire<br>
                      while trying to light a candle set on the cloth was the day Marina discovered the<br>
                      path that was laid out for<br>
                      her by the Gods, who hadn't consulted Marina's mother in the decision...obviously. <br>
<br>
                      After the incident with the tablecloth, Marina's mother sent her out to play while she<br>
                      cleaned up the mess.<br>
                      Marina happily scampered up the many ramps and across the bridges to the platform<br>
                      which held the<br>
                      Scout's guild hall. There she knew she would find her father, a woodelven Scout of<br>
                      Tunare. Her father's<br>
                      &quot;job&quot; had always seemed so mysterious to Marina. As she approached the guild hall,<br>
                      she saw her father<br>
                      striding towards her and quickly ducked into the shadows surrounding anther building<br>
                      close by. As he<br>
                      passed her by without so much as a glance in her direction, she decided to play her<br>
                      favorite game. Moving<br>
                      in the way she had seen her father and other Scout's move, she followed her father<br>
                      to the top of the lift<br>
                      which would take him to the forest. Just as he was about to step onto the lift, she<br>
                      grabbed hold of his<br>
                      long cape. The next thing she knew she was on the ground beneath her father with<br>
                      his dagger at her<br>
                      throat. The look of surprise on her face was mirrored on the face of her father. As he<br>
                      helped her to her<br>
                      feet, he said &quot;You must be careful, my young one, you are lucky that I recognized<br>
                      you before I drove the<br>
                      dagger home.&quot; He then told her to run home and gather her things and present<br>
                      herself to the Scout's for<br>
                      training. He then stepped onto the lift and descended into the forest below. <br>
<br>
                      Marina's mother was most dismayed by this unexpected turn of events and accused<br>
                      Marina of not trying<br>
                      hard enough to learn the ways of the druid. She told Marina &quot;No daugher of mine and<br>
                      certainly no lady<br>
                      would ever presume to become a ROGUE. Henceforth, you will have no mother and I<br>
                      no daughter.&quot; Marina<br>
                      gathered her few belonging and ran from the house crying. <br>
<br>
                      But her life was to be even more disrupted on this day. When she returned to the<br>
                      guild hall, it was in an<br>
                      uproar. One of their own had been discovered in the company of the leaders of the<br>
                      Orc company. A Scout<br>
                      of Tunare had been seen leading Emporer Crush and the Dark Elven Ambassador<br>
                      D'Vinn around the forest<br>
                      outside the walls of Crushbone. And it was her father. When Marina was finally able<br>
                      to get the attention of<br>
                      the guild master and tell him that her father had sent her, he told her &quot;We accept<br>
                      not the spawn of<br>
                      traitors, now be gone. Before we deliver to you the same fate as we did your father.&quot;<br>
                      With those words,<br>
                      the ties that bound Marina to the city of Kelethin and the Scouts of Tunare were<br>
                      broken and she left the<br>
                      forests of Faydark to make her own way in the lands of Norrath. Now when she<br>
                      returned to Kelethin, it was<br>
                      as a daughter of the world and a rogue who knew no alliance except that of the<br>
                      friendships she had<br>
                      formed along the way. <p>Luck in the Shadows,<br>
<br>
Marina Shadowshield<br>
Wife of Cerawyn Shadowshield<br>
Order of Elder Dragons<br>
Head of Security</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/umarinar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MarinaR</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10> at: 10/23/00 9:35:49 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/umarinar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MarinaR</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Theif of Hearts</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#939393>(10/23/00 9:37:10 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.afreehome.com/ashadows/mar2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Caught</span><hr size=1> Marina had just entered her seventh season of training. Training was difficult to say<br>
                      the least since she<br>
                      had no alliance with any of the established rogue guilds in Norrath. She picked up<br>
                      bits and pieces of<br>
                      information from older rogues and hid in corners of guild halls listening to others<br>
                      receive their instruction to<br>
                      learn her craft. But she had yet to learn the art of pickpocketing. She knew that this<br>
                      skill would serve her<br>
                      well, being alone in the world, but everytime she was caught and forced to flee for<br>
                      her life. It was after<br>
                      one such humilating episode that she met another rogue. One who was to become<br>
                      her mentor, her friend,<br>
                      and eventually her love. <br>
<br>
                      As she fled for her very life once again, a strong arm grabbed her around the waist<br>
                      and pulled her into a<br>
                      shadowy corner. She struggled until a deep, calm voice whispered in her ear, &quot;Do not<br>
                      be afraid and do not<br>
                      move. I shall return to you in a moment.&quot; With that the body she had been pressed<br>
                      up against was gone.<br>
                      She caught the glimmer of light on blades and nothing more. <br>
<br>
                      Marina started slipping through the shadows. There was no way that she was going<br>
                      to stand still and wait<br>
                      to be caught in a trap. She was taken by complete surprise when an iron grip<br>
                      grabbed her arm. &quot;I believe I<br>
                      told you not to move, my little thief&quot;, the same deep voice said. &quot;I am no thief&quot;,<br>
                      Marina was barely able to<br>
                      keep herself from screaming. She tried to struggle but to no avail, she was caught<br>
                      fast. &quot;Come with me<br>
                      and keep quiet. It is not safe for either of us here&quot;, the voice spoke again into her<br>
                      ear. Holding her arm<br>
                      tightly, he fairly dragged her up one street and down another always keeping to the<br>
                      shadows. <br>
<br>
                      Eventually, after so many twists and turns that she was completely lost, he opened<br>
                      a door and led her into<br>
                      a small building. When he struck a match to light a lamp, Marina saw the face of her<br>
                      captor for the first<br>
                      time. He was another woodelf, like herself, although he carried himself with the<br>
                      bearing of one born to the<br>
                      nobility. &quot;Why have you brought me here?&quot; Marina questioned the man. &quot;And who are<br>
                      you?&quot; <br>
<br>
                      &quot;I am one like yourself who walks the shadows. You are good, little thief, but I will<br>
                      make you better.&quot; <br>
<br>
                      &quot;And why would you help me?&quot;, Marina asked. <br>
<br>
                      &quot;To repay a debt to the one who took me in and raised me to what you see now.<br>
                      You may call me<br>
                      Cerawyn. And now, my pretty little thief, you should sleep because tomorrow your<br>
                      training truly begins&quot; <p>Luck in the Shadows,<br>
<br>
Marina Shadowshield<br>
Wife of Cerawyn Shadowshield<br>
Order of Elder Dragons<br>
Head of Security</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/umarinar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MarinaR</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Theif of Hearts</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#939393>(10/23/00 9:39:08 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.afreehome.com/ashadows/mar2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Love?</span><hr size=1> Cerawyn continued to train Marina when time allowed. She had gained sufficient skill<br>
                      to be allowed to go<br>
                      hunting on her own. As she had not yet gained his expertise, they could not hunt<br>
                      together but both<br>
                      always returned, sooner or later, to the small home they had created in the city. <br>
<br>
                      As Marina pushed open the door, her eyes scanned the room. Her disappointment<br>
                      would have shown<br>
                      clearly if anyone was there to see. No trace of Cerawyn was to be found, just a note<br>
                      on the small table. <br>
<br>
                      Marina, <br>
<br>
                      Find the bard named Silquendil. He holds for you a reminder of how much your<br>
                      training has progressed. <br>
<br>
                      Cerawyn <br>
<br>
                      Marina had heard Cerawyn speak of this bard before but always with a trace of anger<br>
                      in his voice.<br>
                      Apparently he was something of a drunkard . &quot;Why would the bard have something<br>
                      for me?&quot; she wondered.<br>
                      Replacing the few pieces of armor that she had removed, she headed back out the<br>
                      door and to the tavern.<br>
                      If the bard wasn't there now, he would be soon. <br>
<br>
                      Marina was correct. She had barely ordered her honey mead and chosen a seat<br>
                      where she could observe<br>
                      the door without being readily noticed, when in walked a bard. When he approached<br>
                      the barkeep, she<br>
                      stood and moved in behind him. Dropping a platinum coin of the bar, she said &quot;Give<br>
                      him what he wants and<br>
                      keep them coming.&quot; To the bard, she said &quot;Come and sit with me, songweaver, and<br>
                      perhaps you can tell<br>
                      me a tale.&quot; The young bard, already swaying slightly on his feet, followed her to the<br>
                      table. <br>
<br>
                      Once seated with his drink in front of him, the bard asked &quot;What story would you like<br>
                      to hear, m'lady?&quot; <br>
<br>
                      &quot;First I must know if you are the one called Silquendil, and don't call me a lady.&quot; <br>
<br>
                      &quot;Aye that be my name, m'lady.&quot; The bard continued as if he had not heard the<br>
                      second part of Marina's<br>
                      statement. <br>
<br>
                      Unconsiously, Marina let a dagger slide from her sleeve. &quot;I said do not call me a lady,<br>
                      no lady&quot; the title was spoken with a sneer, &quot;does what I do and takes such pride in<br>
                      her work&quot; <br>
<br>
                      The bard eyed the dagger warily, drained his tankard and waved to the barkeep for<br>
                      more. Marina spoke<br>
                      again, &quot;I was told to find you, that you had something for me.&quot; <br>
<br>
                      Silquendil looked at her blankly for a moment and then the light of recognition shown<br>
                      in his eyes. &quot;Ahhhh,&quot;<br>
                      he exclaimed, &quot;you would be Cerawyn's love?&quot; <br>
<br>
                      Now it was Marina's turn to stare. &quot;What did you say?&quot; she was finally able to ask. &quot;I<br>
                      was approached by a<br>
                      man named Cerawyn who told me to hold this gift for his love who would come<br>
                      seeking it. I don't know, he<br>
                      something about he and I being family or some such thing&quot;, the bard rambled. &quot;So are<br>
                      you this Cerawyn's<br>
                      love? There is a message that is to go with dagger but I'm to speak it to no one but<br>
                      her.&quot; <br>
<br>
                      &quot;I....I.....I don't know. He's never spoken to me of love but the note he left<br>
                      instructed me to find you, that<br>
                      you held a remembrance of my training. <br>
<br>
                      &quot;Then your name would be Marina? The green eyes are right and I can't see much in<br>
                      this dim light but the<br>
                      hair looks to be a soft red color like he described.&quot; the bard muttered to himself. With<br>
                      that he placed a<br>
                      dagger on the table and slid it towards Marina. Marina looked at it and knew it for<br>
                      what it was. A Scout's<br>
                      Blade. &quot;And the message?&quot; she questioned. <br>
<br>
                      &quot;Ahhh yes. Now what was the message? Hmmmmmm. Oh yes, I remember. That you<br>
                      are to take the blade<br>
                      and use it proudly. Keep it to remember him by if he should not return. He is going on<br>
                      a journey that he has<br>
                      needed to make for a long time. Now the time is right but the way is dangerous. He<br>
                      does not think he will<br>
                      able to return to you and show you how he feels.&quot; Silquendil said, &quot;He also bade me<br>
                      tell you that you<br>
                      should keep yourself safe and that he is proud of you.&quot; <p>Luck in the Shadows,<br>
<br>
Marina Shadowshield<br>
Wife of Cerawyn Shadowshield<br>
Order of Elder Dragons<br>
Head of Security</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/umarinar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MarinaR</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Theif of Hearts</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#939393>(10/23/00 9:40:43 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.afreehome.com/ashadows/mar2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> LOVE</span><hr size=1> Filling the tub with hot water, she slipped into it and felt the heat ease her aching<br>
                      muscles as the oils she had added helped to ease her mind. Her thoughts turned<br>
                      again to the words the bard had said were Cerawyn's. Love? Could it be true? But he<br>
                      was a Scout and a proud one at that. Would he still feel love, if he felt it at all, after<br>
                      he knew of her past and the charges made against her father? Marina still did not<br>
                      believe that her father was guilty but had yet to gain sufficient skills to find out the<br>
                      truth.<br>
<br>
                      The water was becoming decidedly cool when she stopped her thinking. Grabbing a<br>
                      brush from a nearby table, she began to brush out her hair. Suddenly a noise in the<br>
                      other room made her stop. Someone was opening the door and trying to be<br>
                      extremely quiet about it. Stepping out of the tub, she grabbed her shift and pulled it<br>
                      on over her head. Padding to the bed, she picked up the daggers she had dropped<br>
                      there. Moving to the door, she could hear footsteps moving towards her. But not<br>
                      ordinary footsteps, these were the almost silent footsteps of another rogue.<br>
<br>
                      As the door opened, Marina readied her daggers. When a man entered the room, she<br>
                      moved to plunge one if not both daggers into his back. She was extremely surprised<br>
                      when he sidestepped her attack and turned to her. &quot;It seems, little one, that you<br>
                      always feel the need to attack me.&quot; Cerawyn said with a grin. The grin quickly faded<br>
                      as his eyes traveled down Marina's body. Looking down herself to see what had<br>
                      caused the change in his expression, Marina quickly turned her back to him. This was<br>
                      definitely not how she had pictured their reunion.<br>
<br>
                      She was surprised to feel his hands on her shoulder until she realized that he was<br>
                      placing his cloak around her. Still holding her shoulders, he turned to face him once<br>
                      more. Marina's eyes were locked on the floor but with a finger beneath her chin, he<br>
                      raised her face. Green eyes met blue and Marina felt as if she were melting. Gently<br>
                      tracing his thumb along her jaw, he brought his head down to hers. Just as Marina<br>
                      closed her eyes in anticipation, he let her go so abruptly that she nearly fell.<br>
<br>
                      &quot;I'm sorry&quot;, was all he said.<br>
<br>
                      &quot;Sorry? Then the words that the bard spoke were not true?&quot; Marina asked.<br>
<br>
                      &quot;What exactly did he say?<br>
<br>
                      &quot;He gave me a Scout's blade, he said you were making a dangerous journey, and…..&quot;<br>
                      Marina's voice trailed off.<br>
<br>
                      &quot;And?&quot; prompted Cerawyn. He could not remember asking Silquendil to tell her<br>
                      anything else.<br>
<br>
                      &quot;He said you loved me.&quot; Marina said, pulling his cloak more tightly about her.<br>
<br>
                      &quot;By the Gods, can't the young fool do anything right?&quot; Cerawyn shouted. Rigid with<br>
                      anger, he paced the room. A small sound made him turn and look at the woman<br>
                      across the room. Tears coursed down her face as she tried to fight them. Her hands<br>
                      were balled into fists so hard surely the nails must be biting into the palms. More<br>
                      carefully than he had approached anything on his journey, he came to Marina. Taking<br>
                      one hand, he softly pried the fist open and led her to a soft chair. Sitting her down,<br>
                      he said &quot;Marina, you must listen me to now. The words the bard spoke were true. I'm<br>
                      angry because he wasn't meant to say them to you. If I had not returned, knowing<br>
                      that I had loved you would have caused you pain and I don't ever want to be the<br>
